@startuml Nginx CGI with C++ Hello World
title Nginx + fcgiwrap CGI — Inbound Request → Compile C++ → "Hello World"

skinparam sequenceArrowThickness 2
skinparam BoxPadding 10
skinparam NoteBackgroundColor #FFFACD
skinparam NoteBorderColor #DAA520

actor "Client" as Client

box "Web Server" #LightBlue
    participant "Nginx\n(port 80)" as Nginx
end box

box "CGI Bridge" #LightGreen
    participant "fcgiwrap\n(FastCGI → CGI)" as Fcgiwrap
end box

box "OS — new process per request" #LightCoral
    participant "cgi-wrapper.sh\n(CGI script)" as Script
    participant "g++ Compiler" as Compiler
    participant "hello\n(compiled binary)" as Binary
end box

participant "Filesystem" as FS

Client -> Nginx: GET /cgi-bin/ HTTP/1.1

note over Nginx
  nginx.conf:
  location /cgi-bin/ {
    fastcgi_pass unix:/run/fcgiwrap.sock;
    fastcgi_param SCRIPT_FILENAME
      /var/www/cgi-bin/cgi-wrapper.sh;
  }
  Nginx only speaks FastCGI —
  it cannot execute scripts directly.
end note

Nginx -> Fcgiwrap: FastCGI request\nover unix:/run/fcgiwrap.sock\n+ SCRIPT_FILENAME env var
activate Fcgiwrap

note over Fcgiwrap
  fcgiwrap bridges FastCGI → CGI:
  - forks a new OS process
  - sets CGI env vars (REQUEST_METHOD, etc.)
  - pipes stdout back to nginx
  This is the actual CGI executor.
end note

Fcgiwrap -> Script: fork & exec\ncgi-wrapper.sh
activate Script

Script -> FS: locate hello.cpp\n(/var/www/cgi-bin/hello.cpp)
FS --> Script: file found

Script -> Compiler: spawn\ng++ hello.cpp -o /tmp/hello_cgi
activate Compiler
Compiler -> Compiler: parse & compile\nhello.cpp
Compiler -> FS: write binary\n/tmp/hello_cgi
Compiler --> Script: exit code 0
deactivate Compiler

Script -> Binary: exec /tmp/hello_cgi
activate Binary

note over Binary
  hello.cpp:
  ──────────────────────────────
  #include <iostream>
  int main() {
    std::cout << "Content-Type: text/plain\r\n";
    std::cout << "\r\n";
    std::cout << "Hello World\n";
    return 0;
  }
  ──────────────────────────────
  CGI rule: headers first,
  blank line, then body.
end note

Binary -> Binary: write to stdout:\n"Content-Type: text/plain\r\n"\n"\r\n"\n"Hello World\n"
Binary --> Script: stdout captured\nexit code 0
deactivate Binary

Script --> Fcgiwrap: stdout piped back\n"Content-Type: text/plain\r\n\r\nHello World\n"
deactivate Script
Script -> Script: process killed ✗

Fcgiwrap --> Nginx: FastCGI response\n(parsed CGI stdout)
deactivate Fcgiwrap

Nginx -> Nginx: build HTTP response\nstatus → 200 OK\nbody   → "Hello World"
Nginx --> Client: HTTP/1.1 200 OK\nContent-Type: text/plain\n\nHello World

note over Client, FS
  Role summary:
  - Nginx      → web server, speaks FastCGI only
  - fcgiwrap   → CGI executor, bridges FastCGI ↔ CGI
  - cgi-wrapper.sh → CGI script, compiles & runs binary
  - hello binary   → writes the actual response body

  Per-request cost: fork(script) + fork(g++) + fork(binary)
  Real deployments pre-compile and skip the g++ step.
end note
@enduml
